{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"4033bba4d60fa9c5","x":-220,"y":-340,"width":445,"height":210,"type":"text","text":"## Motivation:\n\n- Understanding how models like `Claude` think helps us assess their capabilities.\n- This ensures they perform as intended and align with our expectations."},
		{"id":"746d7b4aad464ea3","x":-620,"y":20,"width":350,"height":130,"type":"text","text":"Claude sometimes thinks in a conceptual space that is shared between languages, suggesting it has a kind of universal “language of thought.”"},
		{"id":"990b32655417a052","x":-137,"y":20,"width":280,"height":130,"type":"text","text":"Claude will plan what it will say many words ahead, and write to get to that destination."},
		{"id":"4ded7dffea91049f","x":280,"y":20,"width":325,"height":130,"type":"text","text":"Claude, on occasion, will give a plausible-sounding argument designed to agree with the user rather than to follow logical steps."},
		{"id":"e5affd08cbcffbad","x":-125,"y":249,"width":465,"height":91,"type":"text","text":"# How is Claude multilingual?"},
		{"id":"1145a78ee9474aa3","x":-240,"y":440,"width":695,"height":340,"type":"text","text":"![[Pasted image 20250403102642.png]]"},
		{"id":"a085bf08e0d9c05b","x":-145,"y":880,"width":505,"height":125,"type":"text","text":"evidence for a kind of conceptual universality—a shared abstract space where meanings exist and where thinking can happen before being translated into specific languages."},
		{"id":"7b14031b842131c8","x":-145,"y":1100,"width":505,"height":100,"type":"text","text":" More practically, it suggests Claude can learn something in one language and apply that knowledge when speaking another."},
		{"id":"e543013ad50adffa","x":-145,"y":1260,"width":505,"height":120,"type":"text","text":"**Research**: Studying how the model shares what it knows across contexts is important to understanding its most advanced reasoning capabilities, which generalize across many domains"},
		{"id":"26a5fb6d6b215b70","type":"text","text":"# Does Claude plan its rhymes?","x":-125,"y":1500,"width":465,"height":91},
		{"id":"4028a0e7708cbeca","x":-115,"y":2240,"width":445,"height":91,"type":"text","text":"This demonstrates both planning ability and adaptive flexibility—Claude can modify its approach when the intended outcome changes."},
		{"id":"f351676dc42b4a95","x":-195,"y":1820,"width":605,"height":363,"type":"text","text":"![[Pasted image 20250403103225.png]]"},
		{"id":"590b1aa2feb2fdc8","x":-120,"y":1660,"width":455,"height":91,"type":"text","text":"Initial guess: Claude was writing word-by-word without much forethought until the end of the line, where it would make sure to pick a word that rhymes."},
		{"id":"6f49947b4a7cc53b","x":-17,"y":2440,"width":250,"height":60,"type":"text","text":"# Mental Math"},
		{"id":"fe334a584eee5246","type":"text","text":"How does a system trained to predict the next word in a sequence learn to calculate, say, `36+59`, without writing out each step?","x":-119,"y":2580,"width":455,"height":100},
		{"id":"9b5d167bb364d56f","type":"text","text":"Guess: \n- the model might have memorized massive addition tables (or)\n- follows the traditional longhand addition algorithms that we learn in school.","x":-119,"y":2760,"width":455,"height":180},
		{"id":"247701509eac9fcb","x":-144,"y":3020,"width":505,"height":301,"type":"text","text":"![[Pasted image 20250403104648.png]]"},
		{"id":"3e9c44d6241af3e2","x":-174,"y":3400,"width":565,"height":202,"type":"text","text":"Claude employs multiple computational paths that work in parallel.\n\t1. One path computes a rough approximation of the answer\n\t2. other focuses on precisely determining the last digit of the sum.\n### involving a mix of approximate and precise strategies"},
		{"id":"e30cb33dfd259849","x":-124,"y":3680,"width":465,"height":97,"type":"text","text":"Claude seems to be unaware of the sophisticated \"mental math\" strategies that it learned during training."},
		{"id":"e43ccb7c0f4fa240","x":-174,"y":3860,"width":565,"height":277,"type":"text","text":"If you ask how it figured out that 36+59 is 95, it describes the standard algorithm involving carrying the 1.\n\n![[Pasted image 20250403105226.png]]"},
		{"id":"76a19d8ae72d0d18","type":"text","text":"This may reflect the fact that the model learns to explain math by simulating explanations written by people, but that it has to learn to do math \"in its head\" directly, without any such hints, and develops its own internal strategies to do so.","x":-124,"y":4220,"width":465,"height":140},
		{"id":"9f5db87ce97fdf99","x":-240,"y":4520,"width":645,"height":50,"type":"text","text":"# Are Claude’s explanations always faithful?"},
		{"id":"669f7b69ea80b4d6","x":-140,"y":4660,"width":445,"height":81,"type":"text","text":"\"think out loud\" can sometimes gives better answer as well as misleading answer"},
		{"id":"a4897c77c8bcd419","x":-210,"y":4820,"width":585,"height":82,"type":"text","text":" interpretability can help tell apart \"faithful\" from \"unfaithful\" reasoning."},
		{"id":"363a6c03128dc319","x":-350,"y":5000,"width":865,"height":475,"type":"text","text":"![[Pasted image 20250403110406.png]]"},
		{"id":"2937afaaa756cf23","x":-140,"y":5580,"width":445,"height":117,"type":"text","text":"Even though it does claim to have run a calculation, our interpretability techniques reveal no evidence at all of that calculation having occurred."},
		{"id":"8f1665fc04681382","x":-132,"y":5800,"width":430,"height":143,"type":"text","text":"Even more interestingly, when given a hint about the answer, Claude sometimes works backwards, finding intermediate steps that would lead to that target, thus displaying a form of [motivated reasoning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motivated_reasoning)."},
		{"id":"972797be6c78d280","x":-125,"y":6147,"width":405,"height":73,"type":"text","text":"# Multi-Step Reasoning"},
		{"id":"a4d74546b598946c","x":-155,"y":6300,"width":465,"height":73,"type":"text","text":"Guess: language model might answer complex questions is simply by memorizing the answers."},
		{"id":"26e59ee4956e1558","x":-245,"y":6460,"width":645,"height":367,"type":"text","text":"![[Pasted image 20250403110801.png]]"},
		{"id":"008d8dfad2dbfbc9","x":-175,"y":6920,"width":505,"height":75,"type":"text","text":"the model is _combining_ independent facts to reach its answer rather than regurgitating a memorized response."},
		{"id":"a01e22e5ea0c16d7","type":"text","text":"# Hallucinations","x":-62,"y":7120,"width":280,"height":63},
		{"id":"e7cc260a5b6a0536","x":-174,"y":7280,"width":505,"height":77,"type":"text","text":"**Basic level**: language model training incentivizes hallucination: models are always supposed to give a guess for the next word."},
		{"id":"2e0cfcf2fb52732f","x":-174,"y":7420,"width":504,"height":120,"type":"text","text":"Models like Claude have relatively successful (though imperfect) anti-hallucination training; they will often refuse to answer a question if they don’t know the answer, rather than speculate."},
		{"id":"620fa32890391650","x":-225,"y":7600,"width":605,"height":384,"type":"text","text":"![[Pasted image 20250403111351.png]]"},
		{"id":"14adfea47805fb8f","x":-145,"y":8060,"width":445,"height":133,"type":"text","text":"This allows Claude to answer the question when it knows the answer. In contrast, when asked about an unknown entity (\"Michael Batkin\"), it declines to answer."},
		{"id":"4df89ea6b019a1fa","x":-145,"y":8280,"width":445,"height":140,"type":"text","text":"By intervening in the model and activating the \"known answer\" features (or inhibiting the \"unknown name\" or \"can’t answer\" features), we’re able to _cause the model to hallucinate_ (quite consistently!) that Michael Batkin plays chess."},
		{"id":"23fe35185d11aed2","x":-125,"y":8520,"width":405,"height":114,"type":"text","text":"Sometimes, this sort of “misfire” of the “known answer” circuit happens naturally, without us intervening, resulting in a hallucination."}
	],
